%%TITLE
Human papillomavirus in oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinomas in Korea: use of G1 cycle markers as new prognosticators.
%%ABSTRACT
Human papillomavirus (HPV)-related oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma (SCC) exhibits distinct patterns worldwide, but its prevalence has not been extensively evaluated in Korea. The E7 oncogene-mediated carcinogenesis and its meaning are yet to be uncovered for oropharyngeal SCCs.In a Korean oropharyngeal SCC cohort, epidemiological indicators, HPV, and G1 cell cycle marker expressions were correlated with survival.Among 93 surgically treated patients with oropharyngeal SCCs, 49.5% were HPV+, which were significantly younger, and predominantly nonsmoking. They demonstrated better survival than HPV- (94% vs 60%). Patients who were HPV+ with oropharyngeal SCCs expressed higher p16, cyclin-dependent kinase 4 (cdk4), and lower pRb. The p16 (hazard ratio [HR] 2.39), pRb (HR 2.13), and CCND1 (HR 2.09) correlated with survival. Notably, combined markers like p16/cdk4 ratio (HR 2.47) and cdk4+CCND1 sum (HR 2.65) were more significantly correlated.Incidence of HPV-related oropharyngeal SCC in Korea is similar to U.S.-European data. HPV presence correlates with improved survival. Expression ratios of G1 markers may predict survival of oropharyngeal SCCs better than each marker alone.
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
Subjects and material
Tissue samples from 93 patients with previously untreated, surgically resectable oropharyngeal SCC at the Head and Neck Oncology Clinic, National Cancer Center, Goyang, Korea, were obtained from surgeries performed between 2002 and 2007 (80 men; 13 women; age, 44–85
years; mean age, 62.1 6 8.6 years). Archived paraffin-
embedded specimens were used. Inclusion criteria con- sisted of surgically resectable cases which received full planned surgery based treatment. Radiation was given when surgical margins were positive or close (<2 mm), demonstrated perineural or lymphovascular invasion, or
any stage N2 neck disease, or neck disease with extracap- sular extension. Exclusion criteria were: recurrent, unre- sectable cases, cases with distant metastasis, initially (chemo)radiated cases, or cases that failed to receive the full course of therapy.
Clinical information was obtained using the 2002 American Joint Committee on Cancer staging criteria.13 Histologic grading was performed by 2 pathologists according to the World Health Organization criteria.14 All patients were examined by head and neck surgeons at each follow-up (every 3 months). The institutional review board in accordance with the Center for Clinical Trials, National Cancer Center, Korea, approved this study. All patients gave written informed consent to allow examina- tion of tissues and medical records.
Cumulative alcohol use was calculated as follows: a drink equivalent was one 12-oz beer, one 6-oz glass of wine, one 3-oz Korean spirit (soju), or one 1.5-oz of liq- uor. The number of drink equivalents (hereafter called ‘‘drinks’’) per week was determined within each 5-year age interval and combined into a measure of lifetime alcohol use, defined as the number of years during which
15 or more drinks per week were consumed. We calcu- lated cumulative tobacco use in pack-years using informa- tion about the cigarette use (in 5-year intervals) and gaps in use. Eastern Cooperative Oncology Group (ECOG)/ Zubrod performance status15 and pretreatment hemoglobin levels were measured as parameters reflecting pretreatment health.
DNA extraction
DNA was extracted using QIAamp Mag Attract DNA Mini M48 Kit (Qiagen, CA). Carcinoma tissue was punched out from sections of paraffin blocks to obtain the highest percentage of tumor, carefully avoiding cross-contamination. DNA was extracted using Qiagen BioRobot M48 worksta- tion (Qiagen, CA). The quality and quantity of the DNA was measured using Nanodrop ND 1000 (NanoDrop Technolo- gies, Wilmington, DE). The polymerase chain reaction (PCR) used 10 lL of purified DNA.
Human papillomavirus genotyping in human papillomavirus chip
HPV genotyping was done using a polymerase chain reaction (PCR)-based DNA microarray system (Green- cross, Gyeonggi, Korea), consisting of multiple probes of the HPV L1 sequence, as manufacturer’s protocol.16 This contains specific probes from high-risk (HPV-16, 18, 31, 33, 35, 39, 45, 51, 52, 53, 56, 58, 59, 66, and 68) and
low-risk types (HPV-6, 11, 34, 40, 42, 43, 44, 54, and 70). Consensus PCR products were hybridized to the probes on the chip, scanned (Scanner GX, PerkinElmer, MA), and then analyzed.
Immunostaining and scoring
Tissue microarray was constructed as described.17 Im- munohistochemical (IHC) staining was then performed as summarized in Table 1. IHC expression was scored by 2 pathologists (W.S.P. and G.K.L.), blinded to the clinical outcome, using semiquantitative composite scoring system as follows: (1) the staining intensity was defined as 0 for negative, 1 for weak, 2 for moderate, and 3 for strong (Figure 1); (2) the positive area was defined as the (10 X) fraction of stained tumor cells in the entire tumor; (3) expression score was defined as the staining intensity mul- tiplied by the positive area. The highest possible score was
30. A high expression of each marker was defined by a score 2:20.
Statistical Analysis
The relationship between HPV status and clinical pa- rameters or expression of molecular markers was ana- lyzed using the Fisher exact test or the Pearson chi- square test. For the univariate analyses, rank-based methods were used. The Kaplan–Meier method and the log-rank or Breslow test were used to compare survival rates. Cox regression models were used to estimate haz- ard ratios (HRs) and 95% confidence intervals (CIs) for multiple variables, after adjustment. STATA/SE version
10.1 (StataCorp LP, College Station, TX) were used. Two-tailed p values <.05 were considered significant.
